fr:mainmatter.fr:p: The regular coimage of a map x\xrightarrow {f} y is always a quotient, which we write x/\ker f. The inuition is that the kernel pair is (in Set-like settings) like the set of pairs of elements of x which agree in y, and so the coequalizer is like the set of nonempty fibers of f.
Let \{x_i \xrightarrow {\text {d}_i} x_{i - 1}\} be a chain complex in an abelian category A. The nth chain homology is the "quotient of the n-cycles by the n-boundaries".

Thinking of the kernel of \text {d}_n as the n-cycles and the image of \text {d}_{n + 1} as the n-boundaries, reading the cokernel as the quotient \operatorname {im}\text {d}_{n + 1} / \ker \text {d}_n explains the slogan.
The cohomology of a cochain complex is defined dually.
Regular categories have a (regular epi, mono) factorization system.
The regular image \operatorname {im} f of a map x\xrightarrow {f}y is the equalizer of its cokernel pair, when this exists.
A quotient object x/r is the coequalizer of a congruence r\xrightarrow {r_1,r_2} x.
The kernel pair of a morphism x\xrightarrow {f} y is the pullback of f along itself:
A coequalizer is a colimit of a diagram of shape \bullet \rightrightarrows \bullet .
The category of sets Set is the category whose objects are sets and whose morphisms are set-functions.
